UID:solid@cfgmgmtcamp.eu
SUMMARY:Applying SOLID principles to Infrastructure as Code
ORGANIZER:Bram Vogelaar
CATEGORIES:talk
DTSTAMP:20181227T000000Z
TZID:Europe-Brussels
DTSTART:20190204T173000
DTEND:20190204T182500
DESCRIPTION:"S.O.L.I.D is an acronym for the first five object-oriented design(OOD) principles by Robert C. Martin, in the early 2000s.  These principles, when combined together, make it easy for a programmer to develop software that are easy to maintain and extend.  They also make it easy for developers to avoid code smells, easily re-factor code, and are also a part of the agile or adaptive software development.  This talk discusses our options how we can model puppet code while applying the SOLID principles.  As the puppet DSL is not a object oriented language we will also address the limitations of the design pattern,which we ll have to solve using the convention over configuration design pattern.  "
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:@"<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC ""-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN""><HTML><BODY><p>S.O.L.I.D is an acronym for the first five object-oriented design(OOD) principles by Robert C. Martin, in the early 2000s.</p><p>These principles, when combined together, make it easy for a programmer to develop software that are easy to maintain and extend.<br />They also make it easy for developers to avoid code smells, easily re-factor code, and are also a part of the agile or adaptive software development.</p><p>This talk discusses our options how we can model puppet code while applying the SOLID principles.<br />As the puppet DSL is not a object oriented language we will also address the limitations of the design pattern,which we ll have to solve using the convention over configuration design pattern.</p></BODY></HTML>";
